Latest Articles






Strategies

                    Trump Immigration Crackdown Is Great for Private Prison Stocks                
The worse the news for immigrants and their lawyers, the better it has been for the two publicly traded companies that operate for-profit prisons.
By JEFF SOMMER













Editorial

                    Under Mr. Trump, Private Prisons Thrive Again                
These facilities are morally repugnant and in many ways worse than state-run prisons. The president just gave them a big boost.
By THE EDITORIAL BOARD













Strategies

                    Trump’s Win Gives Stocks in Private Prison Companies a Reprieve                
In the market rally after Donald J. Trump was elected president, two big beneficiaries were operators of prisons and immigration detention centers.
By JEFF SOMMER














                    U.S. to Phase Out Use of Private Prisons for Federal Inmates                
The Justice Department cited a decline in federal prisoners and a critical recent report about safety and security problems in for-profit facilities.
By CHARLIE SAVAGE














                    Using Jailed Migrants as a Pool of Cheap Labor                
As the federal government cracks down on immigrants in the country illegally and forbids businesses to hire them, it is relying on tens of thousands of those immigrants each year to provide essential labor.
By IAN URBINA













Lens

                    An Immigrant’s Dream, Detained                
As the United States deports record numbers of immigrants, John Moore looks at a newly opened detention center.










Letter

                    Crossing the Border, and Into Federal Prisons                
Grassroots Leadership urges that people arrested crossing the border not be tried in criminal courts.











                    After Protests, Prison Firm Pulls Donation                
Florida Atlantic University announced that the GEO Group Foundation, the charitable arm of the private prison corporation, planned to withdraw a $6 million gift to name its stadium.










The Quad

                    Florida Atlantic Students Protest GEO Deal                
Florida Atlantic students have been protesting the school’s decision to sell the naming rights to the football stadium to a private prison company.











                    A Company That Runs Prisons Will Have Its Name on a Stadium                
Florida Atlantic University will name its football building GEO Group Stadium, after the prisons corporation, leading critics to wonder just how far colleges and teams will go for revenue.
By GREG BISHOP


















                    A Halfway House Built on Exaggerated Claims                
The founder of Community First Services in Brooklyn has left a trail of exaggerated claims and self-dealing.










Op-Ed Contributor

                    Can Privatization Kill?                
Controlling borders and immigration have long been a key function of the state, but they are increasingly being taken over by private contractors — with dangerous results.
By THOMAS GAMMELTOFT-HANSEN














                    Companies Use Immigration Crackdown to Turn a Profit                
Private security companies have turned the detention of unwanted immigrants into a multinational industry with a history of abuse.










DealBook

                    GEO to Buy Cornell Companies for $685 Million                
The GEO Group, a prison services provider, said on Monday that it would buy a rival, Cornell Companies, for cash and stock worth $685 million.










National Briefing | Southwest

                    Texas: Inmate’s Family Wins $42.5 Million Judgment                
A private prison company, must pay $42.5 million to the family of an inmate who was beaten to death in 2001 at a Texas facility in Willacy County while prison officials stood idle.











                    Panel to Discuss Concerns on Contractors                
A House subcommittee will examine flaws in the federal procurement system that let contractors with poor performance records renew contracts.











                    Immigration Enforcement Benefits Prison Firms                
Private  prison operators are jockeying for a bigger piece of the growing business of detaining immigrants.











                    Stock Offerings This Week                
The following equity and convertible debt offerings are expected this week:.











                    George Wackenhut, 85, Dies; Founded Elite Security Firm                
George R. Wackenhut, a former F.B.I. agent who built the Wackenhut Corporation into an international security firm that promoted the use of private guards at prisons, airports and nuclear power plants, died on Dec. 31 at his home in Vero Beach, Fla. He was 85. The cause was heart failure, said his daughter, Janis Wackenhut Ward.











                    Security Drill at Weapons Plant Raises Safety Questions                
In the predawn hours of Sept. 2, at the plant that stores the nation's stockpile of highly enriched uranium, guards wearing body armor and carrying loaded submachine guns were dispatched to intercept a group of men who had apparently set off an intrusion alarm. But the target group turned out to be a second team of guards, who were conducting a mock attack with laser-tag equipment. The armed guards, a ''shadow force'' maintained in reserve during such drills, rushed through the dark, ready, people involved said, to shoot at a group whom they believed were intruders.










